<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,260,285]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[353,641,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platystylum">
<emphasis box="[353,641,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Allometopon platystylum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost entirely brown dorsally with a white antenna, yellow anteromedial region of the frons, and one pair of elongate yellow spots on the supra-alar row behind the suture. Similar pale scutal stripes are seen in 
<taxonomicName box="[574,697,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunatum">
<emphasis box="[574,697,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">A. lunatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[712,808,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 137 – 142" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1846]" captionTargetId="figure@93.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 137 – 142. Allometopon lunatum spec. nov., holotype; 137: photo, dorsal; 138: same, lateral; 139: external genitalia, left lateral; 140: inner surface right surstylus; 141: external genitalia, posterior; 142: internal genitalia, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258791/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[765,808,332,356]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" value="137.0">137</number>
</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[830,975,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginale">
<emphasis box="[830,975,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">A. marginale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[991,1087,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 184 – 187" captionStartId="100.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[155,1397,193,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@100.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="100" captionText="FIGURES 184 – 187. Allometopon marginale Sasakawa, holotype; 184: photo, dorsal; 185: same, lateral; 186: inner surface surstylus; 187: internal genitalia, left lateral. Illustrations from Sasakawa (1974)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258798/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[1044,1087,332,356]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" value="184.0">184</number>
</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1149,1309,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phenomena">
<emphasis box="[1149,1309,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">A. phenomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1325,1423,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 212 – 218" captionStartId="105.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1831]" captionTargetId="figure@105.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="105" captionText="FIGURES 212 – 218. Allometopon phenomena spec. nov.; 212: paratype male (with complete transverse yellow stripe), photo, dorsal; 213: holotype, photo, dorsal; 214: same, lateral; 215: paratype, external genitalia, left lateral; 216: same, posterior; 217: internal surface surstylus; 218: internal genitalia, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258803/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[1378,1423,332,356]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" value="213.0">213</number>
</figureCitation>
), but in these taxa the stripes are slightly longer and curve inwards to follow the transverse suture. The surstylus is immediately diagnostic, being broad, flat, slightly incurved posteriorly, and nearly as large as the epandrium in profile. The internal terminalia are unusual, characterized by a parallel set of sclerotized “arms” derived from sternite 
<number box="[242,256,476,501]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" value="6.0">6</number>
that follow the outer surface of the hypandrial arms, the pregonite is flat and twisted, the postgonite is bifid apically (also seen in 
<taxonomicName box="[453,590,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horridum">
<emphasis box="[453,590,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">A. horridum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<figureCitation box="[605,698,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 113 – 119" captionStartId="89.[151,262,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1846]" captionTargetId="figure@89.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURES 113 – 119. Allometopon horridum spec. nov., holotype; 113: photo, dorsal; 114: same, lateral; 115: external genitalia, left lateral; 116: same, posterior; 117: inner surface right surstylus; 118: internal genitalia, ventral; 119: same, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258787/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
Fig. 
<number box="[656,698,512,536]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" value="118.0">118</number>
</figureCitation>
) and the paraphallus is smooth and similarly split apically.
</paragraph>
